# Architecture Rules

## Layering (strict)

- `src/app` — routes only. Pages and route handlers validate (Zod), authorize
  (`requireOrg()`), and delegate. **No business logic.**
- `src/features/*` — feature-based domain UI (one folder per engine: properties,
  site-plan-studio, maps, demographics, marketing, tenants). Components, hooks,
  schemas.
- `src/server/services` — all business logic. **The only layer that imports Prisma.**
- `src/server/providers` — adapter interfaces + implementations for all third parties
  (storage, maps, demographics, AI, PDF rendering). **No third-party SDK usage outside
  this folder.**
- `src/components/ui` — shared design system primitives.

## Multi-Tenancy (mandatory)

- Every tenant-owned table carries `organizationId`.
- Services receive an org-scoped context and must filter **every** query by
  `organizationId`. Never trust client-supplied IDs as a tenancy boundary — always
  verify the row belongs to the caller's organization.

## No Duplication

- No duplicated business logic: if logic exists in a service, call the service.
- No duplicated data models: one Prisma model per concept; shared Zod schemas between
  client forms and API validation (`src/features/*/schemas`).
- Before writing a utility, check `src/lib` for an existing one.

## Extensibility

- Heavy/long-running work goes through the `Job` table + `enqueue()` — never block a
  request on rendering or external fetches.
- Provider swaps (Google → ESRI, S3 → R2) must be configuration changes only. If a
  change requires touching callers, the abstraction is wrong.

See `docs/system-architecture.md`.
